SIMPLE: warm
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Warm
<hw>Warm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Warmer</adjf>; <pos>superl.</pos> <adjf>Warmest</adjf>.]</amorph>
<ety>[AS. <ets>wearm</ets>; akin to OS., OFries., D., & G.
<ets>warm</ets>, Icel. <ets>varmr</ets>, Sw. & Dan. <ets>varm</ets>,
Goth. <ets>warmjan</ets> to warm; probably akin to Lith.
<ets>virti</ets> to cook, boil; or perhaps to Skr. <ets>gharma</ets>
heat, OL. <ets>formus</ets> warm. <?/<?/<?/, <?/<?/<?/.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Having heat in a moderate degree; not cold as,
<xex>warm</xex> milk.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Whose blood is <xex>warm</xex>
within.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Warm</qex> and still is the summer night.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having a sensation of heat, esp. of gentle heat;
glowing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Subject to heat; having prevalence of heat, or
little or no cold weather; <as>as, the <ex>warm</ex> climate of
Egypt</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Fig.: Not cool, indifferent, lukewarm, or the like,
in spirit or temper; zealous; ardent; fervent; excited; sprightly;
irritable; excitable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mirth, and youth, and <qex>warm</qex> desire!</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Each <qex>warm</qex> wish springs mutual from the heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They say he's <qex>warm</qex> man and does not care to be mad<?/
mouths at.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I had been none of the <qex>warmest</qex> of partisans.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthor<?/<?/.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Violent; vehement; furious; excited; passionate;
<as>as, a <ex>warm</ex> contest; a <ex>warm</ex> debate</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Welcome, daylight; we shall have <qex>warm</qex> work on't.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Being well off as to property, or in good
circumstances; forehanded; rich.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Warm</qex> householders, every one of them.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You shall have a draft upon him, payable at sight: and let me tell
you he as <qex>warm</qex> a man as any within five miles round him.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>In children's games, being near the object sought
for; hence, being close to the discovery of some person, thing, or fact
concealed.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here, indeed, young Mr. Dowse was getting
⟦ldquo⟧<qex>warm</qex>,⟦rdquo⟧ <?/<?/ children say at blindman's
buff.</q> <rj><qau>Black.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>Having yellow or red for a
basis, or in their composition; -- said of colors, and opposed to
<xex>cold</xex> which is of blue and its compounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Ardent; zealous; fervent; glowing; enthusiastic;
cordial; keen; violent; furious; hot.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warm</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Warm
<hw>Warm</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Warmed</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Warming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>wearmian</ets>. See
<er>Warm</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> ⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To communicate a moderate degree of heat to; to
render warm; to supply or furnish heat to; <as>as, a stove
<ex>warms</ex> an apartment</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then shall it [an ash tree] be for a man to burn; for he will take
thereof and <qex>warm</qex> himself.</q> <rj><qau>Isa. xliv
15</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Enough to <qex>warm</qex>, but not enough to burn.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make engaged or earnest; to interest; to engage;
to excite ardor or zeal; to enliven.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I formerly <qex>warmed</qex> my head with reading controversial
writings.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bright hopes, that erst bosom <qex>warmed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1628 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warm</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Warm
<hw>Warm</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>wearmian</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To become warm, or moderately heated; <as>as, the
earth soon <ex>warms</ex> in a clear day summer</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There shall not be a coal to <qex>warm</qex> at.</q> <rj><qau>Isa.
xlvii. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To become ardent or animated; <as>as, the speake<?/
<ex>warms</ex> as he proceeds</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warm</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Warm
<hw>Warm</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The act of warming, or the state of
being warmed; a warming; a heating.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>
<rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warm-blooded</ent>⟦br⟧
